>
  <h2>From source</h2>
  <p>You need Go installed. Clone the repo and run via <code>go run</code> or the Makefile.</p>
  <pre><code>go run ./cmd/gode version
go run ./cmd/gode
go run ./cmd/gode resume
make run</code></pre>

  <p>
    <code>make run</code> enables local OpenTelemetry tracing by default and exports OTLP/gRPC
    spans to <code>localhost:4317</code>.
  </p>

  <h2>Resume a session</h2>
  <p>
    <code>gode resume</code> opens a compact inline session picker. Type to search, press
    <code>tab</code> to toggle between sessions from the current workspace and all sessions,
    then <code>enter</code> to resume.
  </p>

  <h2>Tracing with Jaeger</h2>
  <pre><code>./jaeger.sh
make run</code></pre>
  <p>Then open Jaeger at <a href="http://localhost:16686">http://localhost:16686</a>.</p>

  <h2>Homebrew</h2>
  <p>
    The formula builds <code>gode</code> from source, so local installs do not need a signed
    binary artifact. To create a local release from a clean working tree:
  </p>
  <pre><code>VERSION=0.1.0 make release-brew
brew install --build-from-source ./Formula/gode.rb</code></pre>

  <p>
    That creates <code>dist/gode-v0.1.0.tar.gz</code>, computes its checksum, and writes
    <code>Formula/gode.rb</code> with a <code>file://</code> URL for local testing. To
    publish a formula update that points at the git tag instead:
  </p>
  <pre><code>VERSION=0.1.0 PUBLISH=1 make release-brew</code></pre>

  <p>
    <code>PUBLISH=1</code> creates tag <code>v0.1.0</code>, rewrites the formula to use the
    git tag and revision, commits <code>Formula/gode.rb</code>, and pushes the tag plus the
    current branch to <code>origin</code>.
  </p>

  <h2>Quick prompt</h2>
  <pre><code>make ask PROMPT="summarize this repo"</code></pre>
</DocsLayout>
